repo.description: The most widely used Python to C compiler
repo.name: cython

body:
Fixes https://github.com/cython/cython/issues/4146

It's clear from https://github.com/cython/cython/issues/1213 that this is actually a pretty deep problem that was left slightly ambiguous before (because the order of C operations is undefined).

Here I'm mostly focusing on getting name-lookup to be evaluated in the correct order, since assignment expressions make it very, very easy to break those. I'm not worried so much about other side effects (although it probably won't be too hard to try to cope with those with the same mechanism).

For name-lookups I can directly work out what variables are modified by assignment expressions. Any function call is treated as able to modify captured and global variables.

There are definitely cases that I could optimize but don't - C function calls can't modify captured variables (because you can't have C inner functions) and it'd probably also be possible to reason about argument order.

This change also allowed a simplification to the implementation of assignment expressions (previously it avoided an optimization of NameNodes to pass one of the CPython tests, but that's now handled in this transform)

commit.message: Initial go at fixing some evaluation order
Cleaned up remembered state into a class

Avoid protecting builtins

This was preventing useful optimizations

Exclude lhs of assignment nodes

It was causing problems and wasn't useful
Fixed issue with named expression comprehensions
Don't do deepcopy - just copy the sets
Python2 compatible+changed pure version on test

Avoid de-optimizing builtin calls more

By identifying them a bit better, and handling proxy nodes
Changes to where proxynodes are used

title: Try to fix evaluation order (somewhat)
